+## Normalized Test-Family Ledger
+
+### Frozen Normalization Choices
+
+- `[VERIFIED]` All four Step-4 families live on the same canonical one-bridge
+  role-labeled helical packet
+  `P_n = (A_n, B_n, C_n, D_n, E_n)`
+  with mandatory conjugate completion.
+- `[VERIFIED]` All four families are read on the same desired-channel ledger:
+  `A -> B`,
+  `A -> C`,
+  `B,C -> C`,
+  `C,A <-> D`,
+  `D,D -> E`,
+  together with the same forced spectator classes
+  `mirror`,
+  `companion`,
+  `feedback`,
+  `cross`.
+- `[INFERRED]` The canonical gauge is:
+  `|A_n(0)| = 1`,
+  `arg A_n(0) = 0`,
+  one frozen role order,
+  one conjugate-representative convention,
+  and one family-declared helical sign sheet.
+- `[INFERRED]` Any family with nonzero on-template production is transported by
+  the allowed whole-sheet exact scaling to the normalized activation window
+  `I = [0, 1]`
+  with
+  `int_I D_on(t) dt = 1`.
+  Families with
+  `int_I D_on(t) dt = 0`
+  are marked `inadmissible-static` and are not counted as positive witnesses.
+
+### Families Actually Tested
+
+| Family | Type | Frozen definition | Why allowed | Cases covered |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
+| `F_BM` | anti-circuit | exact Beltrami-aligned mirror-complete role packet with static nonlinear forcing ledger | allowed because Step 4 explicitly requires Beltrami cancellation and mirror completion, and the live-activity filter was frozen before outcomes | `Beltrami cancellation`, `mirror-mode completion` |
+| `F_DT(delta, eta)` | anti-circuit | nearly-degenerate one-bridge family with `0 < eta << delta << 1`, weak late desired channels, tiny trigger, and full spectator closure retained | allowed because Step 4 permits explicit parameter families so long as they stay finite-time and packet-complete on the frozen sheet | `nearly degenerate triads`, `tiny trigger modes` |
+| `F_SS(mu)` | pro-circuit | engineered-sign sparse-triad family with `0 < mu <= 1/12`, sign-coherent desired channels, and `O(mu)` spectators on the same window | allowed because the attack packet demanded a friendly helical-sign / sparse-geometry stress family and the family was frozen before any outcomes were read | `engineered helical sign patterns`, `sparse triad geometries` |
+| `F_SL(rho)` | pro-circuit | scale-separated family with `0 < rho <= 1/12`, nonzero but `O(rho)` leakage, and the same frozen packet sheet and window | allowed because Step 4 explicitly permits parameter families with leakage that may be dynamically negligible on one fixed finite window | `scale-separated packets`, `dynamically negligible leakage` |
